    <activity xml:id="act-domain-trap">
        <title>The Domain Trap</title>

        <introduction>
            <p>
                Not every logarithmic equation is what it seems. The nine equations below
                can all be approached algebraically<mdash/>but some of them are
                <term>booby-trapped</term>: the algebra produces an answer that is secretly
                invalid. Your job is to find which equations are trapped, and explain exactly
                why.
            </p>
            <p>
                Recall the golden rule: for <m>\log_b(A)</m> to be defined, the argument
                must satisfy <m>A \gt 0</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <task xml:id="task-domain-trap-solve">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve each of the nine equations below algebraically. Show your working
                    clearly, and write down <em>every</em> solution the algebra produces.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p><m>\log_3(x+2)+\log_3(x-4)=3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_3(x+4)=2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_3(-x^2-1)=2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_2(x^2+2x)=3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_2(x)+\log_2(x+2)=3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_2(3x-1)=4</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_2(x-5)=\log_2(3-x)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_4(x)+\log_4(x-6)=2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log_3(x-6)=\log_3(2x-5)</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    Full algebraic working for all nine equations follows, labelling the top left number 1 and proceeding left to right, top to bottom.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 1:</alert>
                    <m>\log_3(x+2)+\log_3(x-4)=3</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\log_3\!\bigl((x+2)(x-4)\bigr) \amp= 3</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x+2)(x-4) \amp= 27</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 - 2x - 8 \amp= 27</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 - 2x - 35 \amp= 0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x-7)(x+5) \amp= 0</mrow>
                </md>
                <p>Algebra gives <m>x = 7</m> or <m>x = -5</m>.</p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 2:</alert>
                    <m>\log_3(x+4)=2</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x + 4 \amp= 3^2 = 9</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= 5</mrow>
                </md>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 3:</alert>
                    <m>\log_3(-x^2-1)=2</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>-x^2 - 1 \amp= 9</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 \amp= -10</mrow>
                </md>
                <p>
                    No real solutions from the algebra. Note also that the argument
                    <md>-x^2-1 \leq -1 \lt 0</md> for all real <m>x</m>, so the domain is
                    empty before any algebra is attempted.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 4:</alert>
                    <m>\log_2(x^2+2x)=3</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x^2 + 2x \amp= 2^3 = 8</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 + 2x - 8 \amp= 0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x+4)(x-2) \amp= 0</mrow>
                </md>
                <p>Algebra gives <m>x = 2</m> or <m>x = -4</m>.</p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 5:</alert>
                    <m>\log_2(x)+\log_2(x+2)=3</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\log_2\!\bigl(x(x+2)\bigr) \amp= 3</mrow>
                    <mrow>x(x+2) \amp= 8</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 + 2x - 8 \amp= 0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x+4)(x-2) \amp= 0</mrow>
                </md>
                <p>Algebra gives <m>x = 2</m> or <m>x = -4</m>.</p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 6:</alert>
                    <m>\log_2(3x-1)=4</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>3x - 1 \amp= 2^4 = 16</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{17}{3}</mrow>
                </md>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 7:</alert>
                    <m>\log_2(x-5)=\log_2(3-x)</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x - 5 \amp= 3 - x</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x \amp= 8</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= 4</mrow>
                </md>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 8:</alert>
                    <m>\log_4(x)+\log_4(x-6)=2</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\log_4\!\bigl(x(x-6)\bigr) \amp= 2</mrow>
                    <mrow>x(x-6) \amp= 16</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 - 6x - 16 \amp= 0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x-8)(x+2) \amp= 0</mrow>
                </md>
                <p>Algebra gives <m>x = 8</m> or <m>x = -2</m>.</p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 9:</alert>
                    <m>\log_3(x-6)=\log_3(2x-5)</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x - 6 \amp= 2x - 5</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= -1</mrow>
                </md>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-domain-trap-check">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each equation, check whether every logarithm argument is strictly
                    positive for your solution(s). Complete the table below.
                </p>
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <col width="8%"/>
                    <col width="28%"/>
                    <col width="40%"/>
                    <col width="24%"/>
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Eqn</cell>
                        <cell>Algebraic solution(s)</cell>
                        <cell>Domain check (is every argument <m>\gt 0</m>?)</cell>
                        <cell>Verdict</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row><cell>1</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>2</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>3</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>4</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>5</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>6</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>7</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>8</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>9</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                </tabular>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <tabular halign="left" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <col halign="center" width="8%"/>
                    <col width="26%"/>
                    <col width="42%"/>
                    <col width="24%"/>
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Eqn</cell>
                        <cell>Algebraic solution(s)</cell>
                        <cell>Domain check</cell>
                        <cell>Verdict</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>1</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=7</m> or <m>x=-5</m></cell>
                        <cell>
                            <m>x=7</m>: <m>9\gt0</m> and <m>3\gt0</m> — passes.
                            <m>x=-5</m>: <m>-3\lt0</m> — fails.
                        </cell>
                        <cell>Extraneous (<m>x=-5</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=5</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>9\gt0</m> — passes.</cell>
                        <cell>Valid</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>3</cell>
                        <cell>None</cell>
                        <cell>
                            Argument <m>-x^2-1\leq -1\lt 0</m> for all real <m>x</m>.
                            Domain is empty.
                        </cell>
                        <cell>No solution</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=2</m> or <m>x=-4</m></cell>
                        <cell>
                            <m>x=2</m>: <m>8\gt0</m> — passes.
                            <m>x=-4</m>: <m>(-4)^2+2(-4)=8\gt0</m> — passes.
                        </cell>
                        <cell>Valid (both)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>5</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=2</m> or <m>x=-4</m></cell>
                        <cell>
                            <m>x=2</m>: <m>2\gt0</m> and <m>4\gt0</m> — passes.
                            <m>x=-4</m>: <m>-4\lt0</m> — fails.
                        </cell>
                        <cell>Extraneous (<m>x=-4</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>6</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=\tfrac{17}{3}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3\cdot\tfrac{17}{3}-1=16\gt0</m> — passes.</cell>
                        <cell>Valid</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>7</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=4</m></cell>
                        <cell>
                            <m>x-5=-1\lt0</m> — fails. (Also <m>3-x=-1\lt0</m>.)
                        </cell>
                        <cell>No solution</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=8</m> or <m>x=-2</m></cell>
                        <cell>
                            <m>x=8</m>: <m>8\gt0</m> and <m>2\gt0</m> — passes.
                            <m>x=-2</m>: <m>-2\lt0</m> — fails.
                        </cell>
                        <cell>Extraneous (<m>x=-2</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>9</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=-1</m></cell>
                        <cell>
                            <m>x-6=-7\lt0</m> — fails. (Also <m>2x-5=-7\lt0</m>.)
                        </cell>
                        <cell>No solution</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
                <note>
                    <p>
                        Equations 4 and 5 produce identical quadratic solutions
                        (<m>x=2</m> or <m>x=-4</m>) but have different domain conditions.
                        In Equation 4 the argument is <m>x^2+2x</m>, which equals 8 for
                        <em>both</em> values and is therefore always positive at these points.
                        In Equation 5 the two logarithms require <m>x\gt0</m> and
                        <m>x\gt-2</m> separately, so <m>x=-4</m> is immediately invalid.
                        This contrast is worth discussing as a class.
                    </p>
                </note>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-domain-trap-classify">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Using your completed table, sort the nine equations into three groups:
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <em>All solutions valid</em> — every algebraic solution passes
                            the domain check.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <em>Extraneous solution</em> — at least one algebraic solution
                            is rejected by the domain check, but at least one valid solution
                            remains.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <em>No solution</em> — every algebraic solution (if any) is
                            rejected, leaving no valid answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    <alert>All solutions valid:</alert> Equations 2, 4, 6.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Extraneous solution(s):</alert> Equations 1, 5, 8.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>No solution:</alert> Equations 3, 7, 9.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-domain-trap-justify">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each <q>booby-trapped</q> equation (those in groups 2 and 3),
                    write one sentence explaining <em>why</em> the domain check fails —
                    what specifically makes the rejected solution invalid?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 1</alert> (<m>x=-5</m> extraneous): Substituting
                    <m>x=-5</m> gives <m>\log_3(-3)</m>, which is undefined because the
                    argument is negative.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 3</alert> (no solution): The expression
                    <m>-x^2-1</m> is always at most <m>-1</m> for any real <m>x</m>,
                    so the logarithm has no valid input — the domain is empty before
                    any algebra is attempted.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 5</alert> (<m>x=-4</m> extraneous): Substituting
                    <m>x=-4</m> gives <m>\log_2(-4)</m>, which is undefined; combining
                    the two logarithms using the product law assumed both arguments were
                    positive, and that assumption fails here.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 7</alert> (no solution): Solving gives the clean
                    answer <m>x=4</m>, but substituting back gives
                    <m>\log_2(-1)=\log_2(-1)</m> — both sides are undefined, so despite
                    the algebra appearing to work, there is no valid solution.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 8</alert> (<m>x=-2</m> extraneous): Substituting
                    <m>x=-2</m> gives <m>\log_4(-2)</m>, which is undefined; the negative
                    root satisfied the combined form <m>x(x-6)=16</m> but not the original
                    equation, where each logarithm's argument must be positive individually.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Equation 9</alert> (no solution): Solving gives the clean
                    answer <m>x=-1</m>, but substituting back gives
                    <m>\log_3(-7)=\log_3(-7)</m> — both arguments are <m>-7</m>, which is
                    negative, so no solution exists despite the simple algebra.
                </p>
                <note>
                    <p>
                        Equations 7 and 9 are the most deceptive: the algebra is simple,
                        involves no quadratic, and produces a single clean integer (or near-integer)
                        answer. Students are most likely to skip the domain check on these.
                        Consider asking the class: <q>Which equation type is the most dangerous
                        trap, and why?</q>
                    </p>
                </note>
            </solution>
        </task>

    </activity>

